name: Red-throated Diver
description: A medium-sized diving bird with a slender body and distinctive red throat.
traits: Medium-sized, slender body, red throat patch, long pointed bill.
habitat: Breeds in freshwater lakes and ponds; winters in coastal seas and bays.
diet: Fish, crustaceans, and other small aquatic animals.
spotted_locations: Coastal areas of Scotland, Ireland, and northern England; Arctic regions during breeding.
call: Melancholic wails and wailing howls, especially during breeding season.
seasonality: Summer visitor to northern areas; winters along coasts.
behaviours: Excellent swimmer and diver; rarely seen on land except for nesting.

name: Great Northern Diver
description: A large, powerful diving bird with striking black-and-white plumage and a dagger-like bill.
traits: Large body, black head, white underparts, checkered black-and-white back, sharp bill.
habitat: Breeds on freshwater lakes; winters on coastal seas and estuaries.
diet: Primarily fish; occasionally mollusks and crustaceans.
spotted_locations: Coastal areas in Scotland, Ireland, and southwest England during winter.
call: Distinctive eerie wailing, yodel-like calls often heard during breeding season.
seasonality: Winter visitor to the UK; breeds in northern Canada and Greenland.
behaviours: Expert swimmer and diver; dives to great depths to catch fish.

name: Great Crested Grebe
description: A striking waterbird with a distinctive ruff of feathers and elegant courtship displays.
traits: Medium-sized, long neck, reddish-brown ruff, white cheeks, slender body.
habitat: Lakes, reservoirs, and slow-moving rivers; prefers freshwater.
diet: Fish, aquatic insects, and small crustaceans.
spotted_locations: Widespread across the UK on freshwater lakes and reservoirs.
call: Low growls and a series of repeated, sharp “crick-crick” sounds.
seasonality: Year-round resident in the UK; some populations migrate short distances.
behaviours: Famous for elaborate courtship dances; excellent swimmer and diver.

name: Little Grebe
description: A small, fluffy waterbird with a stubby body and a characteristic “peep” call.
traits: Small size, rounded body, dark brown plumage, chestnut neck in breeding season, short bill.
habitat: Ponds, lakes, slow-moving rivers, and wetlands.
diet: Aquatic invertebrates, small fish, and crustaceans.
spotted_locations: Found across the UK in small freshwater bodies, especially in quieter areas.
call: High-pitched “peep-peep” often heard near reed beds.
seasonality: Year-round resident in the UK.
behaviours: Excellent diver; rarely seen flying and prefers to stay close to cover.

name: Manx Shearwater
description: A sleek seabird known for its graceful flight, dark upperparts, and white underparts.
traits: Medium-sized, long slender wings, dark upperparts, white underparts, and a slightly hooked bill.
habitat: Open ocean; breeds on coastal cliffs and islands.
diet: Fish, squid, and other small marine organisms.
spotted_locations: Breeds on islands off the UK coast, such as Skomer and Skokholm; seen offshore in open seas.
call: Distinctive eerie, wailing calls often heard at night near breeding colonies.
seasonality: Summer breeder in the UK; winters in the South Atlantic.
behaviours: Master of gliding flight; spends most of its life at sea and comes ashore only to breed.

name: Fulmar
description: A robust seabird with stiff-winged flight, resembling a small gull but closely related to petrels.
traits: Medium-sized, tube-nosed bill, pale grey upperparts, white underparts, and stiff wings.
habitat: Coastal cliffs and open ocean.
diet: Fish, squid, and scavenged food such as offal.
spotted_locations: Breeding on cliffs along the northern and western coasts of the UK; often seen gliding over the sea.
call: Guttural, grating “kek-kek-kek” sounds during breeding season.
seasonality: Year-round resident, but more commonly seen near breeding sites in spring and summer.
behaviours: Expert glider; spits foul-smelling oil as a defense mechanism.

name: Gannet
description: A large, striking seabird with a white body, black wingtips, and a distinctive yellowish head. Known for spectacular diving.
traits: Large size, long pointed wings, white body, black wingtips, yellowish head, and sharp beak.
habitat: Open ocean and coastal cliffs during the breeding season.
diet: Fish, especially shoaling species like mackerel and herring.
spotted_locations: Breeding on UK coasts such as Bass Rock, St Kilda, and Bempton Cliffs; seen offshore year-round.
call: Harsh, throaty “arrk-arrk” calls heard mainly at breeding colonies.
seasonality: Breeds in spring and summer; disperses offshore during winter.
behaviours: Famous for plunge-diving from great heights to catch fish; flies with steady wingbeats.

name: Cormorant
description: A large, dark waterbird with a distinctive long neck and hooked bill, often seen drying its wings.
traits: Large, black plumage with a greenish sheen, long neck, hooked bill, and webbed feet.
habitat: Coastal cliffs, estuaries, rivers, and lakes.
diet: Fish, caught by diving underwater.
spotted_locations: Found across the UK, especially along coasts, inland lakes, and rivers.
call: Grunting and croaking sounds, mainly at breeding colonies.
seasonality: Year-round resident in the UK.
behaviours: Skilled diver; often seen standing with wings outstretched to dry.

name: Shag
description: A slender, glossy black seabird with a distinctive greenish sheen and a crest during the breeding season.
traits: Smaller than the Cormorant, slender body, glossy black plumage, greenish sheen, and crested head in breeding season.
habitat: Coastal cliffs and rocky shores.
diet: Fish, especially small species like sand eels, caught by diving.
spotted_locations: Common along UK coasts, especially in Scotland, Wales, and southwest England.
call: Harsh croaks and grunts, mainly at breeding colonies.
seasonality: Year-round resident in the UK.
behaviours: Expert diver; forages underwater and often perches on rocks to dry wings.

name: Bittern
description: A secretive, well-camouflaged heron known for its booming call and preference for reed beds.
traits: Medium-sized, streaked brown plumage, stocky body, and short neck.
habitat: Freshwater wetlands with extensive reed beds.
diet: Fish, amphibians, insects, and other small aquatic creatures.
conservation_status: Least Concern (globally); Amber listed in the UK due to habitat loss.
spotted_locations: Found in wetlands like RSPB reserves (e.g., Minsmere, Ham Wall).
call: Deep, resonant “booming” sound, often heard at dawn and dusk during breeding season.
seasonality: Resident breeder in the UK; numbers boosted by winter migrants.
behaviours: Secretive; uses its streaked plumage to blend into reed beds when disturbed.

name: Little Egret
description: Small, white plumage, slender black bill, black legs, yellow feet, and long neck.
traits: Small, white plumage, slender black bill, black legs, yellow feet, and long neck.
habitat: Estuaries, wetlands, shallow lakes, and rivers.
diet: Fish, amphibians, crustaceans, and insects.
spotted_locations: Increasingly common in southern UK wetlands, estuaries, and coastal areas.
call: A harsh “karrk” sound, mainly heard during flight or near nesting sites.
seasonality: Year-round resident in southern UK; some seasonal movements within Europe.
behaviours: Graceful and active feeder; often seen stirring water with feet to catch prey.

name: Grey Heron
description: A large, elegant wading bird with long legs, a long neck, and a dagger-like bill, often seen standing motionless near water.
traits: Large size, grey plumage, white head with black crest, long legs, and a sharp, yellow bill.
habitat: Wetlands, rivers, lakes, estuaries, and garden ponds.
diet: Fish, amphibians, insects, and occasionally small mammals or birds.
spotted_locations: Found across the UK in wetlands, urban parks, and near water bodies.
call: Harsh, croaking “fraank” call, especially during flight or at colonies.
seasonality: Year-round resident in the UK.
behaviours: Patient and stealthy hunter; stands motionless before striking prey with its bill.

name: White Stork
description: A large, graceful bird with white plumage, black wingtips, and a long red bill and legs, often associated with wetland habitats.
traits: Large size, white plumage, black wingtips, long red legs, and a red, pointed bill.
habitat: Wetlands, grasslands, and agricultural fields; often nests on rooftops or tall structures.
diet: Amphibians, fish, insects, small mammals, and reptiles.
conservation_status: Least Concern (globally); rare visitor to the UK.
spotted_locations: Occasionally seen in southern England; small populations reintroduced in the UK (e.g., Knepp Estate in West Sussex).
call: Generally silent; known for bill-clattering displays, especially at nests.
seasonality: Rare visitor to the UK; more common in mainland Europe during spring and summer.
behaviours: Often seen soaring on thermals; nests communally and uses its bill for clattering communication.

name: Spoonbill
description: A large, elegant white waterbird with a distinctive spatula-shaped bill, often seen wading in shallow water.
traits: Large, white plumage, long spatula-shaped bill, long neck, black legs.
habitat: Wetlands, estuaries, shallow lakes, and lagoons.
diet: Aquatic invertebrates, small fish, and insects.
spotted_locations: Found in a few wetlands in southern England (e.g., RSPB reserves at Minsmere and Titchwell).
call: Generally silent; occasionally makes soft grunting or croaking sounds.
seasonality: Summer visitor to the UK; some populations may stay year-round in mild winters.
behaviours: Feeds by sweeping its bill side-to-side in shallow water; often seen in small groups.

name: Greater Flamingo
description: A tall, striking waterbird with pinkish-white plumage, long legs, and a distinctively curved pink-and-black bill.
traits: Large size, pinkish-white plumage, long neck, long legs, curved pink-and-black bill.
habitat: Shallow lakes, salt pans, lagoons, and estuaries.
diet: Algae, small crustaceans, and plankton, filtered through its specialized bill.
spotted_locations: Rare visitor to the UK; occasionally seen in wetlands, particularly in southern England.
call: Loud, goose-like honking sounds, often heard in flocks.
seasonality: Rare visitor to the UK, typically from Europe or captive populations.
behaviours: Often seen wading in water; feeds by dipping its bill upside-down to filter food.

name: Mute Swan
description: A large, elegant waterbird with pure white plumage, an orange bill with a black knob, and a gracefully curved neck.
traits: Large size, white plumage, orange bill with black knob, long neck, black legs.
habitat: Lakes, rivers, reservoirs, and canals.
diet: Aquatic vegetation, grasses, and small invertebrates.
spotted_locations: Found across the UK in freshwater and slow-moving water bodies.
call: Generally silent; occasional hissing or soft grunting.
seasonality: Year-round resident in the UK.
behaviours: Graceful swimmer; often seen gliding on water; defends territory aggressively during breeding season.

name: Whopper Swan
description: A large, elegant swan with white plumage, a long neck, and a distinctive yellow-and-black bill. Known for its loud, trumpeting call.
traits: Large size, white plumage, yellow-and-black bill, long neck, and black legs.
habitat: Lakes, rivers, and wetlands; frequents estuaries and flooded fields in winter.
diet: Aquatic plants, grasses, and occasionally grains from farmland.
spotted_locations: Winter visitor to the UK, especially in Scotland, Northern Ireland, and northern England.
call: Loud, trumpeting “whoop-whoop” call, often heard in flight.
seasonality: Winter visitor to the UK; breeds in Iceland and Scandinavia.
behaviours: Social in winter, often found in flocks; grazes in fields and feeds in shallow water.

name: Pink-footed Goose
description: A medium-sized grayish goose with a short bill and distinctive pink legs and feet. Commonly seen in large flocks in winter.
traits: Medium size, grey-brown plumage, short pink-and-black bill, pink legs, and feet.
habitat: Estuaries, coastal marshes, and agricultural fields.
diet: Grasses, grains, and roots.
spotted_locations: Winter visitor to the UK, especially in eastern England, Scotland, and parts of Northern Ireland.
call: High-pitched, yelping “wink-wink” calls, often heard in flight.
seasonality: Winter visitor to the UK; breeds in Iceland and Greenland.
behaviours: Feeds in flocks; often flies in V-shaped formations during migration.

name: White-fronted Goose
description: A medium-sized goose with grey-brown plumage, a white patch around the base of its pink bill, and black barring on the belly.
traits: Medium size, grey-brown plumage, white face patch, pink bill, and black belly bars.
habitat: Wetlands, estuaries, coastal marshes, and agricultural fields.
diet: Grasses, grains, and roots.
spotted_locations: Winter visitor to southern England, Wales, and parts of Ireland.
call: High-pitched, laughing “kla-ha-ha” calls, often heard in flight.
seasonality: Winter visitor to the UK; breeds in the Arctic tundra.
behaviours: Often seen in mixed flocks with other geese; grazes in fields and wetlands.

name: Greylag Goose
description: A large, sturdy goose with grey-brown plumage, orange bill, and pale legs. It is the ancestor of most domestic geese.
traits: Large size, grey-brown plumage, orange bill, pale pink legs, and a stocky build.
habitat: Lakes, wetlands, rivers, and agricultural fields.
diet: Grasses, crops, and roots.
spotted_locations: Found across the UK, especially in Scotland and northern England; also reintroduced to southern areas.
call: Loud, honking “aahng-aahng,” often heard in flight or when alarmed.
seasonality: Year-round resident, with numbers boosted by winter migrants from Iceland.
behaviours: Social and often seen in large flocks; grazes in fields and swims gracefully in water.

name: Canada Goose
description: A large, distinctive goose with a black head and neck, white chin strap, and brown body. Widely recognized and common in parks and wetlands.
traits: Large size, black head and neck, white chin strap, brown body, and white underparts.
habitat: Lakes, rivers, wetlands, urban parks, and agricultural fields.
diet: Grasses, grains, aquatic plants, and occasionally small invertebrates.
spotted_locations: Found across the UK in parks, lakes, and rivers; especially common in urban areas.
call: Loud honking “ahonk-ahonk,” often heard in flight or during social interactions.
seasonality: Year-round resident in the UK; originally introduced from North America.
behaviours: Social and often seen in flocks; grazes on land and forages in water; forms strong pair bonds.

name: Brent Goose
description: A small, dark goose with black plumage, a white patch on the neck, and a contrasting greyish belly. Often seen in coastal areas during winter.
traits: Small size, black head and neck, white neck patch, dark plumage, and grey belly.
habitat: Coastal estuaries, salt marshes, and mudflats.
diet: Eelgrass, algae, and other aquatic plants.
spotted_locations: Winter visitor to the UK; commonly seen in southern and eastern England, especially along estuaries.
call: Low, guttural “rrot-rrot” or “crr-crr” calls, often heard in flocks.
seasonality: Winter visitor; breeds in the Arctic and migrates to the UK in autumn.
behaviours: Feeds in flocks on mudflats and estuaries; often grazes in fields near coastal areas.

name: Shelduck
description: A large, striking duck with a white body, chestnut breast band, black-green head, and a red bill. Often seen in coastal wetlands.
traits: Large size, white body, chestnut breast band, black-green head, red bill, and pink legs.
habitat: Coastal estuaries, mudflats, and inland lakes.
diet: Aquatic invertebrates, crustaceans, and small mollusks.
spotted_locations: Found across the UK in coastal areas; particularly common in the Wash, Severn Estuary, and Morecambe Bay.
call: Soft, high-pitched whistles and occasional grunts.
seasonality: Year-round resident in the UK, with some migratory populations arriving in winter.
behaviours: Feeds by dabbling or grazing; nests in burrows or rabbit holes near water.

name: Wigeon
description: A medium-sized duck with distinctive plumage: males have a chestnut head with a creamy crown stripe, and females are mottled brown. Known for their whistling calls.
traits: Medium size, males with chestnut head and creamy stripe, females mottled brown, pale grey body, and pointed tail.
habitat: Wetlands, lakes, estuaries, and coastal marshes.
diet: Aquatic plants, grasses, and occasionally seeds.
spotted_locations: Common winter visitor to the UK; seen in wetlands and estuaries, especially in southern and eastern England.
call: Males produce a distinctive whistling “whee-oo” call; females emit softer growls.
seasonality: Winter visitor; breeds in northern Europe and Asia.
behaviours: Grazes on land near water; forms large flocks in winter.

name: Gradwall
description: A medium-sized dabbling duck with understated, elegant plumage. Males are grey with a black rear end, while females are mottled brown, resembling a female Mallard.
traits: Medium size, males with grey body and black rear, females mottled brown, white wing patch visible in flight.
habitat: Freshwater lakes, ponds, marshes, and reservoirs.
diet: Aquatic plants, seeds, and small invertebrates.
spotted_locations: Found across the UK in wetlands, especially in southern and eastern England.
call: Males produce a short, nasal “rek” sound; females emit quacking calls similar to Mallards.
seasonality: Year-round resident in the UK; numbers increase in winter with migrants from Europe.
behaviours: Feeds by dabbling on the water’s surface or grazing on nearby land.

name: Teal
description: A small, fast-flying duck with males showing a striking green eye patch and chestnut head, and females being mottled brown. Common in wetlands.
traits: Small size, males with chestnut head and green eye patch, females mottled brown, pale underparts.
habitat: Freshwater marshes, lakes, estuaries, and floodplains.
diet: Seeds, aquatic vegetation, and small invertebrates.
spotted_locations: Found across the UK in wetlands during winter; breeding in northern England and Scotland.
call: Males produce a soft, high-pitched “wheep”; females emit a quiet quack.
seasonality: Year-round resident; numbers increase significantly in winter with migrants from northern Europe.
behaviours: Feeds by dabbling in shallow water; often seen in small flocks.

name: Mallard
description: A large, widespread duck with males having a glossy green head and females being mottled brown. Known for their adaptability to urban and rural environments.
traits: Large size, males with green head and yellow bill, females mottled brown, both with blue wing patch.
habitat: Lakes, ponds, rivers, canals, and wetlands.
diet: Aquatic plants, seeds, insects, and small invertebrates.
spotted_locations: Found across the UK in almost all freshwater habitats; common in parks and gardens.
call: Females emit a loud quacking “quack-quack”; males produce quieter, raspier calls.
seasonality: Year-round resident in the UK.
behaviours: Feeds by dabbling on the water’s surface or foraging on land; highly adaptable and often seen in urban areas.

name: Shoveler
description: A medium-sized duck with a distinctive broad, flattened bill used for filtering food. Males have vibrant plumage with green heads, while females are mottled brown.
traits: Medium size, broad shovel-like bill, males with green head and chestnut sides, females mottled brown.
habitat: Shallow wetlands, lakes, and marshes.
diet: Aquatic invertebrates, seeds, and plankton, filtered through its unique bill.
spotted_locations: Found in wetlands across the UK, particularly in southern and eastern England.
call: Males produce a low, soft “took-took” sound; females emit quieter quacks.
seasonality: Winter visitor; smaller numbers breed in the UK during summer.
behaviours: Feeds by sweeping its broad bill side-to-side in shallow water; often seen in small flocks.

name: Garganey
description: A small, elegant dabbling duck. Males have a distinctive white stripe over the eye, while females are mottled brown, resembling a female Teal.
traits: Small size, males with white eye stripe and greyish flanks, females mottled brown, both with a slender profile.
habitat: Shallow wetlands, marshes, and floodplains with dense vegetation.
diet: Aquatic plants, seeds, and small invertebrates.
spotted_locations: Breeding in a few locations in southern and eastern England; more common as a passage migrant in wetlands.
call: Males produce a distinctive short, rattling “crr-crr-crr” call; females are quieter with soft quacks.
seasonality: Summer breeder in the UK; migrates to Africa for winter.
behaviours: Feeds by dabbling or filtering food in shallow water; often found in small, quiet wetlands.

name: Pintail
description: A graceful, slender duck with a long, pointed tail. Males have striking plumage with a brown head, white neck stripe, and grey body, while females are mottled brown.
traits: Medium size, long pointed tail, males with brown head and white neck stripe, females mottled brown.
habitat: Wetlands, lakes, estuaries, and marshes.
diet: Aquatic plants, seeds, and small invertebrates.
spotted_locations: Found across the UK in wetlands during winter, particularly in southern and eastern England.
call: Males produce a soft, whistling “whee-oo”; females emit low quacks.
seasonality: Winter visitor in the UK; breeds in northern Europe and Asia.
behaviours: Feeds by dabbling in shallow water; often seen in small flocks or mixed with other duck species.
